replies.commentText:
She can't go lower and keep the rasp, and obviously can't go higher.

The thing is, she was hitting the notes fine at the end, she absolutely has the range. This is just nerves and/or not being able to hear herself well enough. The backchannel feedback from most singers who've been on the voice has been that the in-ear monitoring takes getting used to and most on the show have never used them before. That, and they don't really have the time to get used to it before they have to perform. That's why you'll see them pulling a monitor out of their ear, it's so they can hear what the crowd mix sounds like because that's what they're used to. 

This is exactly the kind of thing that happens when monitoring is weird and you're nervous.

replies.commentText: This week was terrible, with only a few exceptions (like Jackie Foster). So, I agree with you if we're talking about this week's performances. I would disagree, however, about the season as a whole. During the blinds, battles, and knockouts, the performances were of a much higher quality, comparable to any of the best seasons in the past. I honestly don't know what happened this week to make it so bad.

I get the impression that the live events are a little rushed and the performers/crew/techs don't have enough time to put polish on everything.

Also, IDK what people see in her, because everything Jackie sings sounds like karaoke. 

I'm guessing that most people don't frequent the late-20's mid-30's karaoke scene, but there's nothing Jackie does that's stand-out or exemplary relative to your average good karaoke singer or pop-rock cover band frontman in the bar scene of a similar age.
